      <entry xml:id="entry_ormeg" xml:lang="os" abv:completeness="incomplete">
        <form type="lemma"><orth xml:lang="os-x-digor">ormeg
            (<?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220122T230355+0300" comment="скобочки!"?>wormeg<?oxy_comment_end?>)</orth></form>
        <sense xml:lang="os-x-digor"><usg><lang/></usg><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
            <q>дорогой кафтан из верблюжьей шерсти, надеваемый в особых случаях</q>
            <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">(в эпосе, в исторических песнях)</note>
            <note xml:lang="en" type="comment">(в эпосе, в исторических песнях)</note>
          </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
            <q>an expensive camel wool caftan worn on special occasions</q>
            <note type="comment">(in epic literature, in historical songs)</note>
          </abv:tr></sense>
        <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220122T231202+0300" comment="это у Абаева выделено как пример..."?>
        <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">. Снаряжая Оразмага на сватовство, Нарты надевают на него
          все самое ценное (<w>xæznatæ</w>): одежду — <oRef/>, оружие — <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_cīrq"><hi rend="italic">cerq</hi></ref>(<bibl><ref type="bibl"
              target="#src_СОПам."/><biblScope>II 53, 66</biblScope></bibl>)</note>
        <note xml:lang="en" type="comment">. Equipping Orazmag for matchmaking, the Narts put on him
          all the most valuable things (<w>xæznatæ</w>): clothes — <oRef/>, weapon — <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_cīrq"><hi rend="italic">cerq</hi></ref>(<bibl><ref type="bibl"
              target="#src_СОПам."/><biblScope>II 53, 66</biblScope></bibl>)</note><?oxy_comment_end?>
        <abv:exampleGrp>
          <abv:example>
            <quote>Wærxæg æj (læqwæni) æ ormegi dumæggagi batuxta</quote>
            <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q rendition="#rend_smallcaps">Уархаг его (мальчика) завернул в полу своего ормега</q>
            </abv:tr>
            <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
              <q rendition="#rend_smallcaps">Warhag wrapped him (the boy) in the hem of his
                ormeg</q>
            </abv:tr>
            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_СОПам."/><biblScope>II 76</biblScope></bibl>
          </abv:example>
          <abv:example>
            <quote>æ daræs in ravardtoncæ (Esenæn); e dær sæ æ wæle iskodta, æ ormeg ba æ fæsontæbæl
              ærbagælsta æma sæmæ otemæj racudæj iwazægdonæmæ</quote>
            <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q rendition="#rend_smallcaps">„(Есену) подали его одежду; он надел ее, а на спину
                накинул ормег и в таком виде вышел к ним (гостям) в кунацкую</q>
            </abv:tr>
            <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
              <q rendition="#rend_smallcaps">„(Yesen) was given his clothes; he put it on, and threw
                an ormeg on his back, and went out like this to them (the guests) in the guest
                room</q>
            </abv:tr>
            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_СОПам."/><biblScope>II 127</biblScope></bibl>
          </abv:example>
        </abv:exampleGrp>
        <etym xml:lang="ru">Заимствовано из тюркского или монгольского; ср. <mentioned
            xml:lang="trk"><lang/><w>örmäk</w><w>örmäk</w><gloss><q>ткань из верблюжьей
              шерсти</q></gloss><note type="bibl">(<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Радлов"
                  /><biblScope>I 1242</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="xal"><lang/><w>örmög</w><gloss><q>вид кафтана</q></gloss><note type="bibl"
                  >(<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Ramstedt"
              /><biblScope>300</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="mn"
              ><lang/><w>örmege</w><gloss><q>Mantel</q></gloss><note type="bibl">(<bibl><ref
                  type="bibl" target="#ref_Doerfer"/><biblScope>I
            52</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, от корня
            <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T140210+0300" comment="сделать тюркским или монгольским?"?><w>ör-</w><?oxy_comment_end?>
          <q>плести</q>, <q>ткать</q> (<mentioned xml:lang="ky"><lang/><w>örmök</w><gloss><q>ткацкий
                станок</q></gloss><note type="bibl">(<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Юдахин"
                  /><biblScope>337</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>). Уже в XIV в. (1344 г.)
          свидетельствуется на персидской почве (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
              target="#ref_Salemann. Shams i Fachrii Ispahanensis Lexicon persicum. Казань,"
              /><biblScope>1887, стр. 184</biblScope></bibl>): <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
              ><lang/><w>urmak</w><gloss><q>шерстяной клобук</q></gloss>.<note xml:lang="ru"
              type="footnote"><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Vullers"/><biblScope>(I
                  140</biblScope></bibl> s. v.
              <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T142535+0300" comment="))))))))))"?>ا
              و رم ك<?oxy_comment_end?> „Alii turcicam vocem esse dicunt“) со ссылкой на Borhāni
              Qāti.</note><note xml:lang="en" type="footnote"><bibl><ref type="bibl"
                  target="#ref_Vullers"/><biblScope>(I 140</biblScope></bibl> s. v.
              <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T142535+0300" comment="))))))))))"?>ا
              و رم ك<?oxy_comment_end?> „Alii turcicam vocem esse dicunt“) со ссылкой на Borhāni
              Qāti.</note></mentioned>. Отсюда и
            <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T143844+0300" comment="армянский"?><mentioned
            xml:lang="hue"
          ><lang/><w>vermak</w><gloss><q>одеяло</q></gloss></mentioned><?oxy_comment_end?>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="rus"><lang/><w>ормяк</w><w>армяк</w><note type="bibl">(<bibl><ref
                  type="bibl" target="#ref_Salemann"/><biblScope>op.
            cit.</biblScope></bibl>)</note>. В пользу иранского происхождения всей группы
            высказывается
            <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T144548+0300" comment="small caps хотелось бы"?>Bailey<?oxy_comment_end?>
            (</mentioned><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Bailey._Asica._Suppl."
              /><biblScope>206</biblScope></bibl>, <bibl><ref type="bibl"
              target="#ref_Ambages Indoiranicae"/><biblScope>AION 1959 I <hi rend="italic">2</hi>
              121, прим. 3</biblScope></bibl>).</etym>
        <etym xml:lang="en">A borrowing from Turkic or Mongolian; cf. <mentioned xml:lang="trk"
              ><lang/><w>örmäk</w><w>örmäk</w><gloss><q>camel wool fabric</q></gloss><note
              type="bibl">(<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Радлов"/><biblScope>I
                  1242</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="xal"
              ><lang/><w>örmög</w><gloss><q>a kind of caftan</q></gloss><note type="bibl"
                  >(<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Ramstedt"
              /><biblScope>300</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="mn"
              ><lang/><w>örmege</w><gloss><q>Mantel</q></gloss><note type="bibl">(<bibl><ref
                  type="bibl" target="#ref_Doerfer"/><biblScope>I
            52</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, from the root
            <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T140210+0300" comment="сделать тюркским или монгольским?"?><w>ör-</w><?oxy_comment_end?>
          <q>knit</q>, <q>weave</q> (<mentioned xml:lang="ky"><lang/><w>örmök</w><gloss><q>weaver
                loom</q></gloss><note type="bibl">(<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Юдахин"
                  /><biblScope>337</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>). It has been already
          attested in Persian in XIV century (1344) (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
              target="#ref_Salemann. Shams i Fachrii Ispahanensis Lexicon persicum. Казань,"
              /><biblScope>1887, p. 184</biblScope></bibl>): <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
              ><lang/><w>urmak</w><gloss><q>woolen hood</q></gloss>.<note xml:lang="ru"
              type="footnote"><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Vullers"/><biblScope>(I
                  140</biblScope></bibl> s. v.
              <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T142535+0300" comment="))))))))))"?>ا
              و رم ك<?oxy_comment_end?> „Alii turcicam vocem esse dicunt“) со ссылкой на Borhāni
              Qāti.</note><note xml:lang="en" type="footnote"><bibl><ref type="bibl"
                  target="#ref_Vullers"/><biblScope>(I 140</biblScope></bibl> s. v.
              <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T142535+0300" comment="))))))))))"?>ا
              و رم ك<?oxy_comment_end?> „Alii turcicam vocem esse dicunt“) with a reference to
              Borhāni Qāti.</note></mentioned>. Hence consider the following words:
            <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T143844+0300" comment="армянский"?><mentioned
            xml:lang="hue"
          ><lang/><w>vermak</w><gloss><q>blanket</q></gloss></mentioned><?oxy_comment_end?>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="rus"><lang/><w>ормяк</w><w>армяк</w><note type="bibl">(<bibl><ref
                  type="bibl" target="#ref_Salemann"/><biblScope>op.
            cit.</biblScope></bibl>)</note>.
            <?oxy_comment_start author="julie" timestamp="20220123T144548+0300" comment="small caps хотелось бы"?>Bailey<?oxy_comment_end?>
            speaks in favor of the Iranian origin of the entire group (</mentioned><bibl><ref
              type="bibl" target="#ref_Bailey._Asica._Suppl."/><biblScope>206</biblScope></bibl>,
              <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Ambages Indoiranicae"/><biblScope>AION 1959 I <hi
                rend="italic">2</hi> 121, footnote 3</biblScope></bibl>).</etym>
      </entry>
